-- U.S. Stocks Fall as Growth in Confidence Reduces Fed Speculation
-- B y   M i c h a e l   P .   R e g a n
-- 2012-07-31T14:13:31Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-07-31/u-s-stocks-fall-as-growth-in-confidence-reduces-fed-speculation.html
U.S. stocks retreated for a second
day as a gauge of  consumer confidence  topped estimates, reducing
speculation the Federal Reserve will announce plans for more
stimulus at the end of a two-day meeting tomorrow.  The Standard & Poor’s 500 Index lost 0.2 percent to 1,383
at 10:12 a.m. in  New York   The Confidence Board’s index increased to 65.9 this month
from 62.7 in June, figures from the New York-based private
research group showed today. Economists projected a reading of
61.5, according to the median estimate in a Bloomberg News
survey. The report showed a gain in the share of consumers
anticipating better labor and economic conditions in six months.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Michael P. Regan in New York at 
